It argues that the cultural disappearance of the dead/dying body and the introduction of consciousness as humanity's newfound soul found expression in fictional representations of the relic (object) or relict (person). In the six novels examined in this monograph-Samuel Richardson's Clarissa and Sir Charles Grandison; Sarah Fielding's David Simple and Volume the Last; Henry Mackenzie's The Man of Feeling; and Ann Radcliffe's The Mysteries of Udolpho-the appearance of the relic/relict signals narrative mourning and expresses (often obliquely) changing cultural attitudes toward the dead. Published by Bucknell University Press. Distributed worldwide by Rutgers University Press.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aDeath in literature. 0aEnglish fictiony18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aManners and customsxHistoryy18th century. 0aManners and customszEnglandxHistoryy18th century. 0aMourning customs in literature. 0aRelics in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020 Englishz978311070474708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020z9783110704532oZDB-23-DKU08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP eBook-Package Frontlist 2020z978311069033040uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/9781684481958zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781684481958423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781684481958.jpg  a978-3-11-069033-0  RUP eBook-Package Frontlist 2020b2020  a978-3-11-070471-6  EBOOK 